body:
(Original context from #beginners on the community discord: https://discord.com/channels/273534239310479360/273541522815713281/754496149347368981)

This coercion works fine for `i32`:

```rust
pub fn foo(x: &i32) { drop(x) }
pub fn bar(x: &Box<i32>) { foo(x) }
```

But swapping the `i32` for a `dyn Trait` it fails:

```rust
pub trait Environment { fn foo(&self); }

pub fn takes_ref(x: &dyn Environment) {
    x.foo();
}

pub fn takes_ref_box_calls_ref(x: &Box<dyn Environment>) {
    takes_ref(x);
}
```
https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=c9abcf227f9f0ea87716eb3fd2089b13
```rust
error[E0277]: the trait bound `std::boxed::Box<(dyn Environment + 'static)>: Environment` is not satisfied
 --> src/lib.rs:8:15
  |
8 |     takes_ref(x);
  |               ^ the trait `Environment` is not implemented for `std::boxed::Box<(dyn Environment + 'static)>`
  |
  = note: required for the cast to the object type `dyn Environment`
```

If this is correct as-is -- and I'm not certain what's supposed to happen if the trait is implemented for Box too -- then it would be nice to recommend `takes_ref(&**x)` or similar in this case.
